Definitely an hidden gem! I know it seems random to have a cajun seafood boil place in the middle of an asian neighborhood, but trust me they made GOOD FOOD. My go to is Dungeness crab, shrimp and clams in their whole shebang sauce (cost a little bit extra), get an extra order of rice and you are good to go! Reasonably priced, the waitress looks cold but is actually pretty nice, raw oysters are fresh too surprisingly, they deserved to be more popular.

Finally a boil place that doesn't boil out the flavor. The crab was large,  fresh, and delicious.  Great prices, and sizable portions.  I got the stone crabs but will definitely return to try more.

This place is terrible. The water tasted like it was sitting in a pitcher of garbage (ask for bottled water). They serve you a plastic or styrofoam plate and plastic fork then when you finally order from the menu they up the prices $15 or more dollars each item and say the price just changed. I don't know if its because the place is completely empty and they need the money or if this is just what they do. BUT WHO WANTS TO PAY $55 A PERSON FOR DUNGENESS CRAB IN SOME HOLE IN THE WALL PLACE????  I walked out and can happily say I did not stay long enough to TRY the food.

Not too pleased with this place. It we a little over price for what you get. I spent $68 on two orders one labster tail order and an order of crawfish, which included 2 pieces of corn roughly 2 inches long and 2 1-inch potatoes. In total both orders combined. Trust me I was like "ok where to now for the real food." Lol. If you want to fill yourself in with seafood go to Joe's crab shack and it will be roughly $15 more but you get like 60% more seafood and combinations.
